    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\r\n\r\nLooks like no\r\n\r\n### Feature description\r\n\r\n#### Problem\r\n\r\nSometimes you want to paste something into a comment, you create a new line, press escape to then press `p` and trailing space is removed. Usually, it is a good code style to have space after comment marker.\r\n\r\nIt is even more prominent if you have `comments` extended to include markdown unordered list marker (`setlocal comments=\"b:-\"`). You do what described above and end up with invalid markdown syntax. If you have markdown formatter setup via lsp (e.g. prettier), it considers it invalid and messes up the whole list after formatting.\r\n\r\nSo, in both cases you have to manually reenter the space.\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. `setlocal formatoptions+=r`\r\n2. `nvim test.sh`\r\n3. Enter `# comment`\r\n4. Press `<CR>`\r\n5. Press `<Esc>`\r\n6. Trailing space is removed\r\n\r\n![output](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42828375/209435162-d7d7e552-05c5-490d-ae28-08952b2c615c.gif)\r\n\r\n#### Suggested solution\r\n\r\nAdd another flag to `formatoptions` to keep the trailing spaces after going back to normal mode.\r\n\r\n#### P.S.\r\n\r\nApparently it happens [in this function](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/9be24110f68abc111c87c88d82f50f64a1d3ecdd/src/nvim/change.c#L1030-L1030). Since I am not very familiar with C, I was trying to blindly debug it to no avail. \r\n\r\nIf someone can point me to where this occurs, I am willing to try and make a PR.",
